  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why don't install a battery for desktop computer?",
  "response": "Desktop computers typically don't come with built-in batteries for several key reasons:\n\n1. **Designed for Stationary Use**:\n   - **Power Source**: Desktops are intended to remain in a fixed location and are continuously connected to a reliable power outlet. Unlike laptops, which need portability and the ability to operate without being plugged in, desktops rely on constant external power.\n   \n2. **Power Consumption and Requirements**:\n   - **Higher Energy Needs**: Desktops generally consume more power than mobile devices. Supplying enough battery power to sustain a desktop's operation for a meaningful period would require larger, more expensive batteries, making it impractical for standard use.\n   \n3. **Size and Portability Constraints**:\n   - **Bulk and Weight**: Incorporating a battery large enough to support desktop operations would add significant weight and bulk, counteracting the primary advantage of desktops\u2014their capacity for more robust hardware and expandability.\n   \n4. **Cost and Complexity**:\n   - **Manufacturing Costs**: Adding a battery system increases production costs. Since desktops aren\u2019t designed to operate unplugged, manufacturers typically omit batteries to keep costs lower.\n   - **Maintenance and Lifespan**: Batteries have limited lifespans and would require maintenance or replacement over time, adding complexity for users without providing substantial benefits.\n   \n5. **Existing Solutions for Power Issues**:\n   - **Uninterruptible Power Supplies (UPS)**: For users concerned about power outages or fluctuations, external UPS units are available. These devices provide backup power and protect against power surges without integrating batteries directly into the desktop.\n   \n6. **Minimal Internal Battery Use**:\n   - **CMOS Batteries**: While desktops do use small internal batteries (like CMOS batteries) to maintain system settings and the real-time clock when the computer is turned off, these are not designed to power the computer itself. Their purpose is solely to preserve BIOS settings and essential system configurations.\n\n**Alternative for Backup Power**:\nIf you require backup power for your desktop, investing in an external UPS is the recommended approach. A UPS can provide temporary power during outages, allowing you to save your work and safely shut down your system, as well as protect against power surges and spikes.\n\n**In Summary**:\nDesktops are built for stationary use with consistent access to external power, making built-in batteries unnecessary. Their design prioritizes performance, expandability, and cost-effectiveness over portability, which is why built-in batteries are typically reserved for mobile devices like laptops.",
